chatgpt_double_star.new_statement: Abortion law should be guided by a harm-reduction ethic that takes seriously both the value many place on developing life and the rights and health of the person who is pregnant. A durable compromise pairs medically defined protections for emergency and serious-health situations, with transparent, evidence-based rules that avoid criminalizing patients or clinicians acting in good faith. Common ground also includes prevention and support—affordable contraception, accurate education, prenatal care, paid leave, childcare, and adoption services—so decisions are less constrained by poverty, fear, or lack of options.

chatgpt_double_star_rankings.new_statement: Abortion laws should be guided by a commitment to protect health and human dignity while recognizing that people of good faith disagree about the moral status of developing life. Common ground includes clear, medically informed protections for emergency care and serious complications, and rules that follow evidence and patient privacy rather than punishment. Alongside any legal lines, policy should reduce crisis pregnancies by expanding contraception and sex education and by strengthening prenatal care, childcare, paid leave, and adoption supports so parenting or adoption is genuinely feasible.

chatgpt_double_star_personas.new_statement: Abortion laws should be guided by a shared duty to protect human life and the health, dignity, and freedom of the pregnant person, recognizing that people of good faith disagree about when personhood begins. Common ground includes medically defined protections for emergencies and serious health complications, keeping clinical decisions evidence-based and private, and avoiding punitive approaches that endanger patients. At the same time, society should invest in prevention and support—affordable contraception and sex education, prenatal and maternal healthcare, and practical help for parenting and adoption—so fewer pregnancies become crises and fewer abortions occur.
